title: For Sale:  Colombian madsen m1947
postcontent: Colombian m1947 madsen. The left side of the receiver is marked “Madsen M. G./A."  and “Cal. .30”. it is actually chambered in 30-06. The chamber crown is marked “Fuerzas Armadas / DE / Columbia” for Naval Forces of Columbia. the actual date this rifle was produced is 1958. it is very clean but only has a few places on the stock that is messed up very minor though..   This is a Madsen Model 1947 rifle, built by the Danes as part of a 1958 military contract for the Columbian Navy, as indicated by the markings on the chamber ring. This rifle is also known as the Columbian Model 1958. These rifles are often referred to as the “last bolt action military rifle”, as they were based on new engineering from scratch. Strangely, the Danes did not adopt this rifle as their own. Instead, they sold it to developing nations with limited budgets. The muzzle brake, upgraded sights and recoil pad are original. These rifles are rare.   one sold on www.gunauction.com for $506.00.. HERE IS THE LINK TO THAT AUCTION.   http://www.gunauction.com/buy/11855291/guns-for-sale-curios-relics/curios-relics-rifles/colombian-m1947-madsen-bolt-action-rifle-rare-.30-06-springfield-c-and-r

Visit us online: www.BlackhawkTactical.org

Phase # 1 Saturday November 8th 2014

Class Starts: 9am / Class Ends: 7:30pm

 Live Fire Qualifications are held in this phase of the course. Students are asked to bring their firearm  and 50 rounds of factory ammo with them on Day #1 and leave them safely secured out of plain view within their vehicle during the classroom portion. If you do not drive to our facility please check your firearm in with our staff prior to entering the classroom, all checked firearms will be returned at the end of the day and will be utilized on the range.  If you do not own a firearm one will be provided or rentals are avilable at the range we utilize. Please review the bottom of this page for address and directions to the range. 

Our experts designed this course to provide both beginner and advanced shooters with the knowledge, skills and attitude necessary for safely owning and carrying a firearm for personal protection. This classroom is primarily marksmanship and safety based to provide our students with the fundamentals needed to become an accurate marksman while applying the safety principles taught throughout this course. Shooting fundamentals are broken down on an individual basis allowing students to make corrections and increase accuracy before stepping onto the gun range. Our course exceeds Illinois State Police Requirements and we welcome beginners to our program and those who have experience in the handling/shooting of firearms.

PHASE I : TOPICS COVERED

Pistol Components: Semi-Automatic  Revolver Pistol Actions: Semi-Automatic  Revolver  Pistol Functions: Semi-Automatic Revolver Ammunition Components 
Personal Protection Ammo Selection Ammunition Malfunctions Tap/Rack/Assess Practical Drills One/Two Handed Grip

 Hold Control Trigger Control Breath Control 
Fundamental Follow Through  Benchrest Postion Isosceles Position Weaver Position(s)  
Range Safety Protocol Pistol Cleaning: Semi-Automatic Revolver Pistol Storage: Home and Automobile Firearm Safety Rules 

 During Phase I you will go hands on various times  to demonstrate loading/unloading of both semi-automatics and revolvers, safety fundamentals marksmanship skills prior to the live firing portion of this class. To do this you will utilize SIRT dryfiring technology in our classrooms that is used by Swat Teams, Military Branches and Law Enforcement during training drills.  The SIRT pistol is a fully weighted, semi-functional Glock 17 replica, 100% inert with laser feedback. This technology is excellent in providing instant feedback on aim (sight picture and sight alignment) , trigger control, hold control, breath control and follow through fundamentals. This advanced technology allows us to preserve a safe environment for our students while incorporating real world scenarios where practice and fundamental implementation saves lives! 

 dfsf.jpg

  Training Day #2  - Sunday November 9th  2014 

Class Starts 11am / Class Ends 5pm (Approx)  



Phase II of this course implements all of the fundamentals learned in the first portion of our course. Defensive shooting skills require a more refined, advanced approach and you will learn how to utilize the skills you have demonstrated and apply them to a potential lethal encounter. The skills and tactics taught in this portion of the course will ensure not only you stay safe while carrying your firearm but also ensures that those around you are safe as well.  

The course concludes with our Federal and State legal instruction. Immediately following dismissal you will have the option to be fingerprinted and have your application completed with our assistance. You walk out of our classroom 100% done and waiting on your permit. We encourage all of you to continue your training long after our course and are always welcome back to our classroom sessions at any time 100% FREE of charge. title: For Sale:  S&W 41, A series, Trailside or Xesse alternative
location: Far NE IL, Illinois, United States
postcontent:
S&W 41 heavy barrel, not the earliest A series and with the lighter blue box. 1 magazine. Perfect function.  Among the most accurate production, S&W origin M41 ever seen.

Finish is about 95%, due to 2 areas of defect in the bluing on the left that are very hard to see in the photos and a third imperfect area at the pin above the grip area.  These are two light splotches of discoloration to the blueing on the left side and the area around the pin, that are very difficult to see.  An image with these enhanced and marked can be emailed if requested.

As a later A series gun, this one does NOT have a cocking indicator.

For those considering a Hammerli (Walther) Trailside or Xesses but who want a far more accurate and durable gun, this and the other S&W 41 are a "must consider" alternative.  Heavier than a plastic gun, they also are far more durable and more accurate.  Single stage trigger, but adjustable pull weight.

Includes SN matched box, but with no innards.  Please note, the gun has German proof marks, and US re-import marks.

FFL transfer only, even if buyer has an IL FOID card.

The early A series were made by S&W in their first if many transitional buyouts. The company had been taken over by Chris Craft / Bangor Punta at that time. Some drop in quality, but still excellent and among the best made in the USA.  This gun is slightly more accurate than the prior "true" S&W guns, and probably better than anything made in the next series guns and later.

These guns are "similar" to the Hammerli 208 and 212, and are based on the same original versions (Walther Olympia, itself based on the Reising Target Pistol most likely).

They are not as accurate as the 208, do not offer the adjustable trigger, but at least parts are easier to find.  Cost is about the same as the Hammerli 208 or Walther GSP.  This is the heavy barreled version, so feel is a bit heavier than the Hammerli 208 with an 80 gm weight.  Also, the barrel is a little shorter.

Two non-letter series (true Smith and Wesson before the sequence of take-overs) also available. Email for information. Price is higher, comes with SN matched box.

Other target guns (Hammerli, Walther, SIG-Hammerli P240, SAKO) also available. Please email if list is desired.

A detailed catalog of all of the several S&W41 (1 A series, two no letter guns) and additional high resolution images of this gun can be emailed, if you provide an email address.

Shipping is $30 unless combined with other guns.

"Close" offers considered.

title: For Sale:  .32 ACP +P Ammo - 75 gr. Hardcast F.N. (1150fps/ M.E. 220 ft. lbs.) - 20 Round Box
postcontent:
https://www.extreme-impact-ammo.com/index.php?l=product_detail&p=132

.32 ACP +P Ammo - 75 gr. Hardcast F.N. (1150fps/ M.E. 220 ft. lbs.) - 20 Round Box

The 32 ACP auto inhabits a valuable and useful place in our society as a defensive cartridge, mostly because of the easily concealable, tiny pistols chambered for it. HOWEVER, because of the very limited size of the cartridge, it is plagued with limited power and therefore most of the existing ammo in 32 ACP suffers from not being reliable as a man-stopper. We've studied and examined nearly all available 32 ammo and find it wanting as a reliable means of self defense, especially against a large, drugged up/pain free, determined attacker.

Here's the problem. The current 32 ACP frangible ammo delivers a large amount of surface trauma, but lacks sufficient penetration. For example, if you shot me or another sane man in the face, with modern, frangible 32 ACP ammo, it would blow off a big portion of my cheek. I would undoubtedly fall to the ground in shock and pain, but I would be very much alive and functional if I could get past the pain, as that frangible bullet would have stopped somewhere in my face, never making it to my brain. However, if you shot a drugged up maniac in the face with that same frangible bullet and blew half his cheek off, he would keep right on coming because he is insane and is not thinking like you or I. Plus, he is likely pain free and fear free and won't know that part of his cheek is missing and if he did know, he would not care. So, whatever 32 ACP ammo you shoot him in the face with, had better go through his face and blow his brain stem out the back of his head, because only a CNS (central nervous system) hit with a 32 ACP is going to stop him. Likewise, a torso hit to the sternum needs to penetrate deep enough to blow all the way through his spine in order to shut him down instantly. If you fail to shut him down instantly, you and your loved ones are going to have to find a way to survive while you wait for him to bleed out and pass out. The best chance of survival for you and your loved ones, is to shut down the attacker instantly. So, we've designed this 32 ACP+P load to keep you and yours alive under the worst of scenarios.

This 32 ACP+P ammo will better all American made 32 ACP+P ammo by 110 fps to 150 fps with a heavier bullet than any other American made 32 ACP ammo.

Item 30A/20 is a 75gr. HARD cast bullet with a flat nose. It is traveling over 1,000 fps out of my 3.4 inch Beretta Mod. 70. We've used a flash suppressed powder so that you won't be blinded by your own gunfire in the dark. This is significant as well over 90% of all civilian shootings in America occur in low light when the criminal element is out and about. Also, this flat nosed, nonexpanding, hard cast, bullet will penetrate deeply and will do much more damage than the typical round nosed FMJ bullet. Round nosed bullets tend to slip and slide through living tissue, doing little damage as opposed to a flat nosed bullet. The flat nose not only wounds much more than a round nosed bullet, but it actually keeps the penetration straight and thus deeper. Notice the below velocities from my personal 32 ACP pistols. These are real world guns and thus the speeds are realistic and not the exaggerated speeds you'll see produced from laboratory test barrels. What you see with Buffalo Bore Ammo advertising, is truly what you get in the "real world" where it matters. You can expect 20+ inches of straight line penetration in flesh and bone with this load. If you are worried about over-penetration with this load, DON'T! You chose to carry a tiny under-powered 32 ACP pistol and the trade off is that now you are going to have to stay alive using this pistol and over-penetration will be the least of your worries if you end up needing this gun to save yourself or your family.

A. Berretta Mod. 70, 3 inch bbl.- 1001 fps

B. Kel Tek, 2.5 inch bbl - 910 fps

C. Seecamp, 2 inch bbl. - 856 fps

The above bullet speeds are 110 fps to 150 fps faster than the Winchester 71 gr. FMJ ammo on the American market. Not only is our bullet heavier than any other American made 32 ACP ammo, but it is moving about 15% to 20% faster - with that heavier bullet!
Feeding and function was flawless in the three test pistols listed above.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Star PD .45 REDUCED! If listed I've still got it.
location: Warren to Akron Ohio and around I76/80, Akron, Ohio
postcontent:
This Star PD is the nicest I've seen in quite a while.  I have another in fair condition and got so excited when I saw this one I bought it immediately to replace the other.  Of course, I don't really need it and will probably end up selling the other too.  I will try to get by with just my other four .45s. I would like to find a NAA revolver with both cylinders.  The Star PD is one of the earliest of compact high power handguns predating the polymers and providing a familiar feel to 1911 shooters, which were very common when it came out. It has an alloy frame and is in .45 ACP. The previous owner put friction tape on the front and rear of the grip, which feels good in the hand.  It is very much like a 1911, breaking down in similar fashion but without the grip safety.  (http://www.alpharubicon.com/leo/starpdserger.htm)  Jeff Cooper said it was a gun to shoot a little and carry a lot.  It is slim, light and trim.  It has an adjustable sight.  The bluing, which is too expensive for many new guns, is in very nice shape.  It seems very tight although I have not shot it.  Some of the internet self-appointed experts will say it is not as good as the almighty Glock (what could be) but the PD retains a faithful following among those who have actually had or fired one.  

PS: Saw one that was not as nice at Summit County gun show for 495.

title: For Sale/Trade:  AR-15
postcontent: Basic AR-15, Anderson lower (new), collapsible stock, 1/9 twist 16-inch heavy barrel identified as a "5.56" barrel, A2 sights on fixed carry handle, A2 flash suppressor, and the left-coast feared BAYONET LUG!!. Upper receiver is not new, probably 1000+ rounds over 15+ years, some wear and tear getting moved around in safe and vehicle over the years. Unsure of upper manufacturer, but it came off  a Rock River gun I got in a trade many years ago. Lots of people are really hung up on the manufacturer of every piece and part these days. The gun does NOT have M4 feed ramps (due to its age). The upper/lower finish match up fairly well in spite of the age difference. Very interested in trades toward high-end handguns (HK/Walther/Sig/etc.) with boot going either way to make it work.  This gun would be a perfect platform for someone to finish their customized. I have some upgrade accessories I could use as boot if that's where the new owner would like to take it. I think I have some quadrails, grips, and maybe even a fixed stock. Gun was cycled at the range to ensure everything works flawlessly. This guy simply needs a new home where it can get warmed up from time to time.
